================================================================
PRODUCT REQUIREMENTS DOCUMENT
================================================================
Product       : Gesture Playground
Version       : 1.0 — Level 1 (MVP)
Status        : Draft
Last Updated  : 2026-05-25
================================================================


----------------------------------------------------------------
1. PRODUCT VISION
----------------------------------------------------------------

Gesture Playground is a browser-based, realtime gesture-controlled
3D experience. Users control a virtual 3D environment using only
their hands through a webcam — no mouse, no keyboard, no UI buttons.

The experience itself is the product. There is no dashboard,
no login, no feed. A user opens the site, enables their camera,
and their hands become the controller.

The core promise:
  "What if your hands could reach into a screen and move things?"

Target feeling: futuristic, smooth, experimental, immersive.


----------------------------------------------------------------
2. GOALS
----------------------------------------------------------------

Primary Goals
  [G-01]  Deliver realtime hand tracking at 30fps minimum
  [G-02]  Recognise 7 distinct hand gestures reliably
  [G-03]  Let users spawn, grab, move, and throw 3D objects
  [G-04]  Keep the experience fullscreen and UI-minimal
  [G-05]  Integrate AI to extend the experience meaningfully

Non-Goals (Level 1)
  - No user accounts or saved sessions
  - No multiplayer or shared rooms
  - No mobile support (desktop-only, Level 1)
  - No complex landing page or marketing site
  - No heavy shader or particle effects
  - No AR camera compositing


----------------------------------------------------------------
3. USERS
----------------------------------------------------------------

Primary User
  A developer, designer, or tech-curious person who wants to
  experience something experimental in a browser with no install.
  They are comfortable giving webcam access and expect the thing
  to just work.

User Context
  - Desktop browser (Chrome or Edge preferred)
  - Reasonably lit environment
  - Hands visible in front of camera
  - No special hardware required


----------------------------------------------------------------
4. FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS
----------------------------------------------------------------

4.1  ENTRY EXPERIENCE
---------------------
[F-01]  The site SHALL display a minimal entry screen on load.
        Contents: project name, one-line description, Enter button.

[F-02]  Clicking Enter SHALL trigger a webcam permission request.

[F-03]  If permission is denied, the app SHALL display a clear
        error state with a retry button and an HTTPS note.

[F-04]  If permission is granted, the app SHALL immediately begin
        loading MediaPipe and transition to the experience.

[F-05]  A loading indicator SHALL appear while MediaPipe initialises.

[F-06]  If MediaPipe fails to load (WASM error, network failure),
        the app SHALL display an error state with a retry button.


4.2  HAND TRACKING
------------------
[F-07]  The app SHALL detect up to 2 hands simultaneously.

[F-08]  MediaPipe Hands SHALL run inside a Web Worker using
        OffscreenCanvas to prevent main thread jank.

[F-09]  The app SHALL render a hand skeleton overlay (21 landmarks
        per hand) as a subtle visual layer over the 3D scene.

[F-10]  When no hands are detected, all scene objects SHALL freeze
        in place. Nothing shall reset or glitch.

[F-11]  Hand landmark data SHALL be posted from the worker to the
        main thread via postMessage at every processed frame.


4.3  COORDINATE MAPPING
-----------------------
[F-12]  A coordinateMapper utility SHALL convert MediaPipe's
        normalised 2D landmark coordinates (0–1 range, camera space)
        into Three.js world coordinates.

        Mapping formula:
          three_x = (mediapipe.x - 0.5) * SCENE_WIDTH
          three_y = -(mediapipe.y - 0.5) * SCENE_HEIGHT
          three_z = mediapipe.z is used for depth hints only

[F-13]  The mapper SHALL be the single source of truth for all
        2D → 3D conversions. No other module shall perform this
        conversion independently.


4.4  GESTURE RECOGNITION
------------------------
[F-14]  The app SHALL detect the following 7 gestures:

        GESTURE               DETECTION METHOD
        ─────────────────     ─────────────────────────────────
        One finger            Index extended, others folded
        Two fingers           Index + middle extended
        Three fingers         Index + middle + ring extended
        Fist                  All fingers folded, thumb across
        Open palm             All five fingers extended
        Pinch                 Thumb tip + index tip distance < threshold
        Both fists            Fist detected on both hands simultaneously

[F-15]  A gesture SHALL NOT fire unless it has been held stable
        for 200 milliseconds (stability threshold).

[F-16]  After a gesture action fires, a 600ms cooldown SHALL
        prevent the same gesture from triggering again.

[F-17]  Current detected gesture name and confidence score SHALL
        be tracked in gestureStore (Zustand).

[F-18]  A semi-transparent gesture hint panel SHALL display in the
        corner of the screen showing:
        - Current detected gesture (name + icon)
        - What it does
        This panel SHALL fade out after 10 seconds of inactivity
        and reappear when no gesture is detected for 3 seconds.


4.5  GESTURE → ACTION MAP
-------------------------
[F-19]  Gesture actions SHALL be mapped as follows:

        GESTURE         ACTION
        ─────────────   ────────────────────────────────────
        Two fingers     Spawn cube at hand position
        One finger      Spawn sphere at hand position
        Three fingers   Spawn torus at hand position
        Fist            Grab nearest object (within threshold)
        Open palm       Release held object / throw
        Pinch           Precise grab of small/distant objects
        Both fists      Clear all objects (scene reset)


4.6  OBJECT SYSTEM
------------------
[F-20]  The app SHALL support 4 spawnable 3D shape types:
        - Cube         (BoxGeometry)
        - Sphere       (SphereGeometry)
        - Torus        (TorusGeometry)
        - Pyramid      (ConeGeometry, 4 radial segments)

[F-21]  Objects SHALL use MeshStandardMaterial with a subtle
        emissive glow. Each shape type SHALL have a distinct color.

[F-22]  The scene SHALL enforce a hard cap of 15 objects.
        When the cap is hit, the oldest object SHALL be removed.

[F-23]  Object spawn SHALL animate from scale 0 → 1 over 200ms.

[F-24]  Spawned objects SHALL maintain their last position when
        hands leave the frame (no reset, no deletion).


4.7  OBJECT INTERACTION
-----------------------
[F-25]  On fist gesture, the app SHALL find the nearest object
        within a grab threshold radius of the index finger MCP
        landmark. That object becomes "grabbed".

[F-26]  A grabbed object SHALL follow the hand's world position
        with lerp smoothing (factor: 0.15) to prevent snapping.

[F-27]  Only one object can be grabbed per hand at a time.

[F-28]  The app SHALL track the hand's world position across the
        last 8 frames (velocityTracker utility).

[F-29]  On open palm gesture (release), the stored velocity vector
        SHALL be applied to the released object as a throw impulse.

[F-30]  Throw impulse magnitude SHALL be clamped to a max speed
        to prevent objects flying out of scene bounds.

[F-31]  A point light SHALL follow the grabbed object, creating
        a subtle glow-transfer visual feedback effect.


4.8  3D ENVIRONMENT
-------------------
[F-32]  Scene background SHALL be solid dark (#0a0a0f).

[F-33]  Scene SHALL include ambient lighting (low intensity)
        and one directional light.

[F-34]  An invisible floor plane at y=0 SHALL prevent objects
        from falling infinitely. (Soft boundary, no Rapier in MVP.)

[F-35]  An optional subtle grid on the floor plane SHALL be
        rendered using Three.js GridHelper.


4.9  PHYSICS (PHASE 7 — NOT MVP)
---------------------------------
[F-36]  Rapier physics (@dimforge/rapier3d-compat) SHALL be
        integrated in Phase 7 only.

[F-37]  Phase 7 physics requirements:
        - Gravity applied to all scene objects
        - Rigid body colliders on all objects
        - Floor plane as static collider
        - Throw velocity → Rapier impulse
        - Object-to-object collision detection

        Rapier SHALL NOT be installed or imported in MVP builds.


----------------------------------------------------------------
5. AI FEATURE REQUIREMENTS
----------------------------------------------------------------

5.1  CUSTOM GESTURE TRAINING  [AI-01]
--------------------------------------
Tool        : TensorFlow.js (on-device, no API calls)
Location    : src/workers/gestureTrainer.worker.ts

[AI-01-a]  Users SHALL be able to define custom gestures by
           holding a new pose steadily for 5 repetitions.

[AI-01-b]  TensorFlow.js SHALL train a lightweight classifier
           in-browser using those 5 samples.

[AI-01-c]  Trained gestures SHALL be stored in localStorage
           and persist across sessions.

[AI-01-d]  Custom gestures SHALL appear in the gesture → action
           map alongside built-in gestures.

[AI-01-e]  Training SHALL occur entirely on-device. No landmark
           data SHALL be sent to any server.


5.2  VOICE COMMANDS VIA CLAUDE API  [AI-02]
--------------------------------------------
Tool        : Claude API (cloud) + Web Speech API
Endpoint    : /api/voice-command (Next.js API route)

[AI-02-a]  The Web Speech API SHALL capture the user's voice
           and transcribe it to text client-side.

[AI-02-b]  The transcribed text plus a snapshot of current scene
           state SHALL be sent to a Next.js API route.

[AI-02-c]  The API route SHALL call Claude with a structured
           system prompt that defines all valid scene actions.

[AI-02-d]  Claude SHALL return a JSON action array:
           [{ action: "spawn", type: "sphere", count: 5,
              arrangement: "circle", radius: 2 }]

[AI-02-e]  The client SHALL parse and execute the action array.
           Invalid or unknown actions SHALL be silently ignored.

[AI-02-f]  Example voice commands the system SHALL handle:
           - "spawn five spheres in a circle"
           - "make everything bigger"
           - "clear the scene"
           - "throw all objects up"
           - "make the cubes orbit the sphere"

[AI-02-g]  A visible microphone indicator SHALL show when the
           system is listening vs processing.


5.3  AI SCENE COMPOSER  [AI-03]
---------------------------------
Tool        : Claude API (cloud)
Endpoint    : /api/compose-scene (Next.js API route)

[AI-03-a]  A minimal text input SHALL allow users to describe
           a scene in natural language.

[AI-03-b]  The description SHALL be sent to Claude which returns
           a complete scene configuration as JSON:
           {
             objects: [
               { type: "sphere", position: [x,y,z],
                 scale: 1.2, color: "#4488ff" },
               ...
             ]
           }

[AI-03-c]  The client SHALL clear the current scene and spawn
           objects as described in the config.

[AI-03-d]  Example prompts the system SHALL handle:
           - "recreate the solar system"
           - "a tower of cubes with a sphere on top"
           - "chaos — lots of small shapes everywhere"
           - "a ring of toruses around a giant sphere"

[AI-03-e]  Object count in AI-generated scenes SHALL be capped
           at the existing 15-object scene limit.


5.4  MOOD-RESPONSIVE ENVIRONMENT  [AI-04]
------------------------------------------
Tool        : On-device heuristic model (no API)
Location    : src/utils/moodEngine.ts

[AI-04-a]  The mood engine SHALL analyse hand velocity and
           movement variance across the last 30 frames.

[AI-04-b]  Two mood states SHALL be computed:
           - HIGH ENERGY  : fast, erratic hand movement
           - CALM         : slow, deliberate hand movement

[AI-04-c]  Mood state SHALL smoothly shift the following:
           - Scene ambient light color temperature
           - Object material emissive intensity
           - Background darkness level

[AI-04-d]  Mood transitions SHALL be eased over 2 seconds to
           avoid jarring changes.

[AI-04-e]  No API calls. No data leaves the browser.


5.5  AI OBJECT PERSONALITY  [AI-05]
-------------------------------------
Tool        : Claude API (cloud)
Endpoint    : /api/object-personality (Next.js API route)

[AI-05-a]  When an object is spawned, the app SHALL call Claude
           with: object type, current scene object count, scene
           mood state.

[AI-05-b]  Claude SHALL return a behavior profile JSON:
           {
             drift: "upward" | "none" | "circular",
             rotation: "slow-spin" | "fast-spin" | "wobble" | "none",
             reactsToProximity: "repel" | "attract" | "none",
             glowPulse: true | false
           }

[AI-05-c]  The scene SHALL apply this behavior profile to the
           spawned object permanently for its lifetime.

[AI-05-d]  API calls for object personality SHALL be fire-and-forget.
           Objects spawn immediately with default behavior, then
           update to AI behavior when the response arrives.

[AI-05-e]  Responses SHALL be cached per object type + mood combo
           to limit API call frequency.


----------------------------------------------------------------
6. NON-FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS
----------------------------------------------------------------

Performance
  [NF-01]  Target 60fps render loop on mid-range desktop hardware.
  [NF-02]  MediaPipe frame processing SHALL not block the main thread.
           Maximum acceptable frame latency: 33ms.
  [NF-03]  Hand landmark → scene update round trip SHALL be < 50ms.

Reliability
  [NF-04]  All camera and MediaPipe failure modes SHALL display
           a user-facing error, never a silent blank screen.
  [NF-05]  The scene SHALL remain interactive even if an AI API
           call fails. All AI features are additive, not critical.

Compatibility
  [NF-06]  Level 1 target browsers: Chrome 110+, Edge 110+.
  [NF-07]  Firefox and Safari are out of scope for Level 1.
  [NF-08]  Mobile browsers are out of scope for Level 1.
           A "best on desktop" guard SHALL appear on mobile viewports.

Security
  [NF-09]  Webcam stream SHALL NEVER be transmitted to any server.
           Only landmark coordinate data (21 points per hand) is
           used in the application logic.
  [NF-10]  Claude API calls SHALL be proxied through Next.js API
           routes. The API key SHALL NEVER be exposed to the client.
  [NF-11]  Custom gesture training data (TF.js) SHALL remain
           on-device in localStorage only.

Accessibility
  [NF-12]  Gesture hint overlay SHALL have sufficient contrast
           for readability.
  [NF-13]  An optional keyboard fallback mode is a future scope
           item, not a Level 1 requirement.


----------------------------------------------------------------
7. TECHNICAL CONSTRAINTS
----------------------------------------------------------------

  [TC-01]  MediaPipe MUST run in a Web Worker via OffscreenCanvas.
           Never on the main thread.

  [TC-02]  Rapier physics MUST NOT be imported in MVP.
           It is Phase 7 only.

  [TC-03]  All gesture logic MUST debounce via the 200ms stability
           threshold + 600ms cooldown. No exceptions.

  [TC-04]  Coordinate mapping (2D → 3D) MUST go through
           coordinateMapper.ts exclusively.

  [TC-05]  Claude API MUST be called only from Next.js API routes,
           never from client-side code directly.

  [TC-06]  Scene object cap MUST be enforced at 15 objects.
           Auto-remove oldest on overflow.

  [TC-07]  Throw impulse MUST be clamped to prevent objects
           exceeding scene bounds.


----------------------------------------------------------------
8. STATE MANAGEMENT SPEC  (Zustand)
----------------------------------------------------------------

sceneStore
  objects          : SceneObject[]
  addObject        : (type: ShapeType) => void
  removeObject     : (id: string) => void
  clearScene       : () => void
  grabbedObjectId  : string | null
  setGrabbed       : (id: string | null) => void

gestureStore
  currentGesture   : GestureType | null
  confidence       : number
  handPosition     : Vector3 | null
  bothHandsVisible : boolean
  setGesture       : (gesture, confidence, position) => void

cameraStore
  permitted        : boolean
  active           : boolean
  error            : string | null
  setPermitted     : (val: boolean) => void
  setError         : (msg: string | null) => void

aiStore
  voiceListening   : boolean
  composerInput    : string
  lastAIAction     : string | null
  mood             : 'calm' | 'high-energy'


----------------------------------------------------------------
9. SUCCESS METRICS
----------------------------------------------------------------

MVP is considered successful when:

  [SM-01]  A user with no instruction can spawn an object
           within 30 seconds of entering the experience.

  [SM-02]  Gesture recognition accuracy is above 85% under
           normal indoor lighting conditions.

  [SM-03]  Scene maintains 60fps with 10 active objects and
           both hands tracked simultaneously.

  [SM-04]  Camera permission → first tracked hand appears
           in under 3 seconds on a standard connection.

  [SM-05]  Zero silent failures — every error state has a
           visible message and a recovery action.


----------------------------------------------------------------
10. OUT OF SCOPE (LEVEL 1)
----------------------------------------------------------------

  - Multiplayer / shared scenes
  - Mobile browser support
  - Authentication or saved sessions
  - Custom GLSL shaders
  - Particle morphing or holographic effects
  - Gesture combo sequences
  - AR (camera compositing over real world)
  - Haptic feedback
  - Hand-drawn gesture recording beyond TF.js training


